p <- length(lm$coefficients)-1 ; n <- dim(df)[1]

1 - (3)

1.Fit the model (WLS model with two-stage estimation)

df_new <- df[-c(44, 49),] # removing (44,49)th observations.
lm_rmvd <- lm(Y ~ X1+X2+X3, data=df_new)
table(df$Region) ; table(df_new$Region)

We have to estimate \(C^2_j\), I know the direct coding is efficient, but to reuse later,

I defined a function that calculate \(\hat{\sigma_j^2}\) and weights

2. Define function to calculate \(\hat{\sigma_j^2}\)

list = c('1', '2', '3', '4')
s_list <- c('s1', 's2', 's3', 's4')
residuals <- lm_rmvd$residuals

calc_sigma_j_sq <- function(x){
  value_count <- length(which(df_new$Region==list[x])) # Calculate length of each groups
  result <- sum(residuals[(df_new$Region==x)]^2)/(value_count-1) # Calculate sigma_j^2_hat
  return(result)
}

3. Calculate weights

for(i in 1:4){
  assign(paste0('s',1:4)[i], calc_sigma_j_sq(i)) 
  # Make(s1,s2,s3,s4) and assign sigma_j^2 values sequentially
  df_new$w[df_new$Region==i] <- 1/get(s_list[i]) 
  # Calculate Weights and assign them to new rows
}
c(s1,s2,s3,s4)
## [1] 1614.8318 2669.2897  245.9945 1157.9857

1 - (4)

To make homogeneous variance structure, If we divide \({\sigma}_{ij}^2\) with \(x^2_{ij1}\), Var(\(\epsilon*_{ij}\))=\({\sigma^2}_{ij^/x^2_{ij1}}\) = \(k^2\).
Then we can define weights as w = \(1/x^2_{ij1}\)

1. Define weights and fit the model

w <- 1/df$X1^2
lm_w <- lm(Y ~ X1+ X2 + X3, data=df, weight=w)
summary(lm_w)
